{{Infobox ethnic group |group = Pakistanis in South Africa |image = |caption = |population = 130,000 |popplace = [[Fordsburg]], [[Laudium]] |langs = [[Saraiki Urdu language|Saraiki]] [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]{{·}} [[Pashto language|Pashto]]{{·}} [[English language|English]] |rels = [[Islam]] }}
'''Pakistanis in South Africa''',<ref>[http://opf.org.pk/download/annual/YEARBK.pdf 2004-2005 Yearbook - Overseas Pakistanis Foundation]{{dead link|date=April 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}. opf.org.pk</ref>{{update after|2013|1|29}} mainly resides in [[Cape Town]], [[Johannesburg]], [[Gauteng]] and [[Durban]].
Many expatriates run [[spaza shop]]s, or [[barber|barber shop]]s; and the [[Johannesburg]]'s [[Fordsburg, Gauteng|Fordsburg]] is said to be among the best places to find Pakistani food. The influx of people arriving from Pakistan has increased significantly in the last 10 years. Most of them are in grocery, electronics and cell phone businesses. They are also running successful business of imported cars from Japan in Durban.<ref>[http://www1.southafrica.net/Cultures/sw-KE/trade.southafrica.net/MoreAboutSA/WhatToDo/Restaurants/Indian_Pakistani.htm Indian/Pakistani - SouthAfrica.net]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In addition to business, many Pakistanis are working in the field of medicine throughout the country. It has often been speculated that various Indian and Pakistani crime syndicates operate within the country,<ref>[http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/uncategorized/indian-pakistani-crime-syndicates-active-in-south-africa_10083034.html Indian, Pakistani crime syndicates active in South Africa]. Tha Indian (2008-08-12). Retrieved on 2015-12-25.</ref> most of whom tend to be involved in drug smuggling. In February 2010, a crowd of angry rioters protesting unemployment issues burnt tyres and barricaded roads in a northern township in Johannesburg; local media reported that Pakistani shopkeepers were among those whose premises were looted.
The Pakistan South Africa Association is a very effective organisation which represents Pakistanis all over South Africa. Its has 16 units which operate its offices from all provinces and has the central executive office in Pretoria. <ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100213180202/http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/the-newspaper/front-page/06-pakistanis-hit-by-rioting-in-south-africa-020-rs-03 Pakistanis hit by rioting in South Africa]. dawn.com (10 February 2010 )</ref>.
