{{Infobox language |name=Sa’ban |region=Borneo |speakers={{sigfig|1960|2}} |date=2000 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Austronesian |fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] |fam3=[[North Bornean languages|North Bornean]] |fam4=[[North Sarawakan languages|North Sarawakan]] |fam5=[[Apo Duat languages|Apo Duat]] |iso3=snv |glotto=saba1265 |glottorefname=Sa'ban }}
'''Sa’ban''' is one of the remoter languages of Borneo, on the [[Sarawak]]–[[Kalimantan]] border. The language is known as ''hmeu Sa'ban'' in the Sa'ban language.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=CLAYRE|first=I. F. C. S.|date=1973|title=THE PHONEMES OF SA’BAN: A LANGUAGE OF HIGHLAND BORNEO|url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/j/ling.1973.11.issue-100/ling.1973.11.100.26/ling.1973.11.100.26.xml|journal=Linguistics|language=en|volume=11|issue=100|doi=10.1515/ling.1973.11.100.26|issn=1613-396X}}</ref>
== Classification == Sa'ban is a member of the [[Apo Duat languages|Apo Duat subgroup of languages]], which also includes [[Kelabit language|Kelabit]], [[Lun Bawang language|Lun Bawang/Lundayeh]] and [[Tring language|Tring]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Language Use and Language Change in Brunei Darussalam|last=Martin|first=Peter|publisher=Ohio University Press|year=1996|isbn=|editor-last=Martin|editor-first=Peter|location=Athens OH|pages=268-279|chapter=A comparative ethnolinguistic survey of the Murut (Lun Bawang) with special reference to Brunei|editor-last2=Oz̊óg|editor-first2=Conrad|editor-last3=Poedjosoedarmo|editor-first3=Gloria}}</ref> Collectively, they belong to the [[North Sarawakan languages|North Sarawak subgroup]] of the [[Austronesian languages|Austronesian family]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Blust|first=Robert|date=1997|title=Ablaut in Northwest Borneo|url=|journal=Diachronica|volume=14|pages=1-30|via=}}</ref> Today, the Sa'ban people live in Long Peluan, Long Banga' and Long Balong in Sarawak, Malaysia. There are also Sa'ban groups in Kalimantan, Indonesia.<ref name=":0" />
== Phonology == The Sa'ban language has several sounds that are rare among the world's languages. These include voiceless nasal and liquid consonants<ref name=":0" /> and a distinction between long and short vowels as well as long and short consonants. Some examples of words with voiceless nasals and liquids are given in the table below. They have a stative reading in contrast to long consonants:<ref name=":0" /> {| class="wikitable" |+Voiceless Nasals and Liquids in Sa'ban ! !Voiceless Continuant (Stative) !Long Consonant (Transitive) |- |{{angle bracket|{{IPA|ɹ̥}}}} |/''hraək''/ {{IPA|[ɹ̥ɹa:k]}} 'torn' |/''rraək''/ {{IPA|[ɹa:k]}} 'to tear' |- |{{angle bracket|{{IPA|ɬ}}}} |/''hləu''/ {{IPA|[ɬləu]}} 'correct' |/lləu/ {{IPA|[ləu]}} 'to steer' |- |{{angle bracket|{{IPA|n̥}}}} |/''hnau''/ {{IPA|[n̥nʌu]}} 'opinion' |/''nnau''/ {{IPA|[nʌu]}} 'to think' |}
